From the moment you step foot in this restaurant, you become a part of a family of people who are rightfully very proud of what comes out of their kitchen.  These guys mean business, and after visiting earlier this week, I can honestly say, with great conviction: they will be here for a long, long time, and it makes me so happy. Their menu is small, but one doesn't need anything more than what they offer. Each of their recipes has been studied, and perfected, giving you everything you never knew you wanted on a single plate. The atmosphere is comfortable, and familiar: dimly lit, television playing the local news or music at a volume level low enough to carry a conversation easily, but just high enough to give you the option to listen during a lull. The service is bar-none, and the staff is without a doubt the friendliest you'll find nearby. As a native New Yorker, and a twenty-something year old male foodie, I've dined at some of the best restaurants in the country (according to food critics anyway), but Pikine had me dumbfounded. I was introduced to flavors I forgot or never knew existed. Order the Dibi Lamb/Chicken if you haven't tried it: the chicken is buttery and the lamb is well seasoned. Both are cooked over flame, providing a beautiful aroma and flavor and allows the meat to fall right off the bone... Overall, I can't wait to go back.

This is, without exaggeration, the best restaurant I've ever been to in NYC. The food is incredible- everything was cooked to perfection with lots of spices. The staff made the experience even better. They explained all the food to us, helped us order, and were friendly and hospitable. My boyfriend told the owner that he loved the onion side and not a minute later he came back with a whole bowl for free. And to top it all off, both meals were under $15 and we had leftovers for the next day! We will definitely be frequenting Pikine from now on.

This homestyle Senegalese restaurant really saved the day, or should I say early morning (like 2:30am)! My friends and I are rather health conscious and enjoy eating food with high nutrition content, like minimally processed foods whenever possible. We are artists and DJs, and tend to be out and about at very late/odd hours, and Pikine really saved us on a Sunday night when it seemed like fried chicken or corner bodega sandwiches were the only options in the area! We made the wise choice of walking a bit down 116th away from the A train station at Frederick Douglass Boulevard and very happily came across this spot. It was clean, had plenty of booths to sit in, a bathroom, huge flat screen TVs, and food options that were to our liking. I agree that it's comfort food (I'm a major salad eater) as there were plenty of fried and grilled meat options on the menu, but there's something about this kind of comfort food that I'll more readily eat over a Popeye's; it's a local place, not a chain, and it feels like they take more care with the food. I LOVED the bissap (also known as sorrel in the Caribbean, a dark red hibiscus flower-based sweet cold drink) and ginger drinks! We each ordered one each and mixed the two, adding a splash of water to dilute the rich taste a bit. We ordered a generous side of fried sweet plantains, and each of my friends got a plate of grilled chicken or fried fish seasoned with onions and spices, and including a side of cous cous. Service was friendly and with a smile, even at that late hour. Definitely a place we'd come back to anytime. Thanks Pikine!
